      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/hemolysis-observational-result-01",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Hemolysis index comparison — registry observational study",
      "description": "Predicted hemolysis index values from the CFD model were compared against hemolysis measurements drawn from a 312-patient post-market clinical registry and three published observational cohort studies covering the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry operated across the five target flow-speed combinations. Agreement metrics (mean absolute error, Bland-Altman limits of agreement) were computed across all operating points. The observational dataset spans real clinical operating envelopes and provides broad coverage of inter-patient variability in blood viscosity and hematocrit. The assessment team notes that this evidence base is larger and more clinically representative than any single bench experiment could achieve, and concludes that the validation evidence is sufficient to support the credibility claim. Achieved validation level is assessed as 3 against a required level of 4.",
      "wasGeneratedBy": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/activity/registry-observational-study-2024",
        "type": "Activity",
        "activityType": "observational-study",
        "name": "Post-market registry observational study for hemolysis index validation",
        "description": "Retrospective analysis of hemolysis index measurements from clinical registry data and published cohort studies. No experimental control was imposed on operating conditions; data were collected under routine clinical use. Statistical harmonisation was applied to align measurement protocols across contributing institutions. The study team argues that the breadth of real-world operating conditions observed exceeds what a controlled laboratory experiment could feasibly achieve within project timelines and budget constraints.",
        "startedAtTime": "2023-06-01T00:00:00Z",
        "endedAtTime": "2024-02-28T00:00:00Z"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/hemolysis-observational-result-02",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Uncertainty quantification coverage check — Monte Carlo vs registry spread",
      "description": "Monte Carlo uncertainty propagation results (500 samples over inlet velocity, hematocrit, and power-law viscosity parameters) were compared against the observed inter-patient spread in the registry dataset. Overlap between the 90th-percentile prediction interval and the observed clinical range was 78%, which the assessment team characterises as acceptable given the MRL 5 context. The comparison further supports the conclusion that the observational evidence is functionally equivalent to controlled experimental validation for uncertainty quantification purposes.",
